@mernst This problem already existed before, but I just notice it when reading through this: isn't this the wrong way around? A @Nullable String is a supertype of @NonNull String, so it is safe for Iterator<@Nullable String> to be a supertype of List<String>.
As described, it sounds like one can assign an Iterator<@Nullable String> to a Iterator<String>, which would then allow to read a value as non-null, even though the iterator can contain nulls.
Am I misreading the example?
